import java.util.* ;
import java.io.*; 
public class Solution {
	public static String zigzagConversion(String s, int row) {
		// Write your code here.
		StringBuilder sb[] = new StringBuilder[row];

		if(row == 1 || row > s.length()){
			return s;
		}

		for(int i = 0; i < row; i++){
			sb[i] = new StringBuilder();
		}

		int currRow = 0;
		boolean goingDown = true;

		for(char ch : s.toCharArray()){
			sb[currRow].append(ch);

			if(currRow == 0){
				goingDown = true;
			}else if(currRow == row-1){
				goingDown = false;
			}

			currRow += goingDown ? 1:-1;
		}

		StringBuilder str = new StringBuilder();
		for(StringBuilder strr : sb){
			str.append(strr);
		}
		return str.toString();
	}
}



You are given a string ‘S’ and an integer ‘ROW’, convert the row into a zig-zag pattern with rows equal to ‘ROW’ and output it row-wise. You may refer to the example below to better
understand what the zig-zag pattern means.

Example :
If ‘S’ = “beaninjacoder” and ‘ROW’ = 4

Then the zig-zag pattern is:
b         j        r
e     n   a     e
a   i     c   d
n         o

Therefore, we will print “bjrenaeaicdno”.



T.C => O(N)
S.C => O(N)
